		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014 SI"></a><br><code>sle2014s/paper06</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Bounded seas</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JanKurš.html">Jan Kurš</a>, <a href="../profile/MirceaLungu.html">Mircea Lungu</a>, <a href="../profile/RathesanIyadurai.html">Rathesan Iyadurai</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarNierstrasz.html">Oscar Nierstrasz</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cl.2015.08.002">10.1016/j.cl.2015.08.002</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2014/paper04.html"><em>Bounded Seas: Island Parsing Without Shipwrecks</em></a> (SLE 2014)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a grammar-based technique (“bounded seas”) for island parsing/semi-parsing, i.e., engineering and composing grammar descriptions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The key technical goal is composability of islands and their surrounding “water”, which is a modularity/composition concern in language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> The technique is motivated by making islands reusable across contexts by generating island-specific “water” automatically.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The approach is presented with tool support by integrating bounded seas into a parser combinator framework.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
